reviews.review_text:
Great quality, great show A great time in dead history for many reasons, early 73 is loaded with inspired shows, and this is one of them.  In my eyes, the Dead hardly had a bad show from E72 until the horns tour of Fall 73.  Maybe one or two, max!  

I am particularly in love with the HCS>China>Rider...a very strong segue into Rider.  Also of interest (to me, anyway) is one of the last Birdsongs of the 70's.  I think the Birdsong is a patch, but still just exactly perfect.  Jerry deftly navigates the solo, and Keith backs him subtly with amazing little flourishes--a nice facet of the Keith and Donna years--phased out in the late seventies as the band leaned into the arena rock juggernaut that they would become in the 80's and 90's.  This show has lovely "tiny music' moments sprinkled throughout, like heaven's pixie dust.  Soak it all in, then come back and tell me it's not just exactly perfect.

Where's The Matrix? I'm scratching me head wondering where the matrix is? Oh well. This guy does a pretty good job of reviewing the show. So I'll defer to him. He's absolutely right about Bird Song and this period for it. Simply gorgeous.
https://dailydoseofdead.wordpress.com/tag/here-comes-sunshine/

There's no shame in being perceived as an average show in this period. This is your basic 3 hour, 29 song monster, great soundboard, great performance. The shows of 1973 just continue to amaze me. To me it is just as good as any from this period. Jerry's solos on PiTB are hot as hell.

My favorite’73 show Garcia’s shreds his best Chuck Berry, Bobby sparkles, the band’s harmonizing like early Beatles, and Phil hasn’t yet lost sense of humor (The Seastones sets were still a blessed 14 months away)
